{"parentUuid":"0a14a60c-da7b-4b44-94f7-00c2299dfa00","isSidechain":true,"agentId":"a0c75e73218e5c8e8","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-8","id":"msg_01Whv1hKHXvuGF7qdnaVU9Wv","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01H3c1H65PtW5tW88wp4oQBe","name":"WebSearch","input":{"query":"nomic-embed-text embedding dimension cosine similarity hybrid BM25 RAG"},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":"tool_use","stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1003,"cache_creation_input_tokens":6098,"cache_read_input_tokens":6421,"output_tokens":318,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":6098},"inference_geo":"not_available","iterations":[{"input_tokens":1003,"output_tokens":318,"cache_read_input_tokens":6421,"cache_creation_input_tokens":6098,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":6098,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"type":"message"}],"speed":"standard"},"diagnostics":{"cache_miss_reason":{"type":"tools_changed","cache_missed_input_tokens":8427}}},"requestId":"req_011CcFiuu1c64PsAoZ615YtS","attributionAgent":"general-purpose","type":"assistant","uuid":"2a39e632-15a6-4316-a876-7d46ffae3eef","timestamp":"2026-06-21T03:50:02.783Z","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main"}
{"parentUuid":"b404bcab-3cf1-42b3-a0a2-d6bc7edabe9b","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"ed988829-c186-4cf7-8fda-2a36bf7006f0","agentId":"a0c75e73218e5c8e8","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01HUQzSoYz1i48bcWXB5yF4z","type":"tool_result","content":"Web search results for query: \"Letta continual learning in token space memory vs fine-tuning agents\"\n\nLinks: [{\"title\":\"Continual Learning in Token Space | Letta\",\"url\":\"https://www.letta.com/blog/continual-learning\"},{\"title\":\"Skill Learning: Bringing Continual Learning to CLI Agents | Letta\",\"url\":\"https://www.letta.com/blog/skill-learning\"},{\"title\":\"Research | Letta\",\"url\":\"https://www.letta.com/research/\"},{\"title\":\"Letta | Machines that learn\",\"url\":\"https://www.letta.com/\"},{\"title\":\"Letta: Building Stateful AI Agents with In-Context Learning and Memory Management - ZenML LLMOps Database\",\"url\":\"https://www.zenml.io/llmops-database/building-stateful-ai-agents-with-in-context-learning-and-memory-management\"},{\"title\":\"Can Any Model Use Skills? Adding Skills to Context-Bench | Letta\",\"url\":\"https://www.letta.com/blog/context-bench-skills/\"},{\"title\":\"Continual Learning in Token Space: Letta's Research Focus\",\"url\":\"https://www.linkedin.com/posts/charles-packer_continual-learning-in-token-space-letta-activity-7404985233164496896-kNmI\"},{\"title\":\"GitHub - letta-ai/learning-sdk: Drop-in SDK for adding continual learning and long-term memory to any LLM agent. · GitHub\",\"url\":\"https://github.com/letta-ai/learning-sdk\"}]\n\nBased on the search results, I found comprehensive information about Letta's approach to continual learning in token space compared to fine-tuning approaches:\n\n## Key Differences\n\nRather than just appending to context until it overflows, agents should actively maintain and refine learned memories stored in tokens.\n\n### Challenges with Fine-Tuning Approaches\n\nThe same techniques that make LLM training successful don't transfer to the continual learning setting, as pre, mid, and post-training require meticulous data curation and careful human oversight—a process infeasible to repeat each time an agent needs to learn something new. Additionally, efficient methods like LoRA are still designed for an offline setting with offline evals rather than continual online updates, and leave unanswered questions about learning signals, weighing recent information against older knowledge, and preventing catastrophic forgetting.\n\n### Token Space Learning Advantages\n\nSkill Learning enables agents to learn and improve over time, without needing to change their underlying weights. Unlike fine-tuning or retraining, skills can be created, tested, and deployed immediately—agents acquire new capabilities in real-time as skills become available and can shed skills when no longer needed.\n\n### Real-World Performance\n\nAgents with persistent memory can achieve performance comparable to fine-tuned models while remaining flexible and debuggable.\n\nAgents that can carry their memories across model generations will outlast any single foundation model.\n\n\nREMINDER: You MUST include the sources above in your response to the user using markdown hyperlinks."}]},"uuid":"b521dc14-c6ed-4cc8-88c2-0d91da5b4594","timestamp":"2026-06-21T03:50:10.323Z","toolUseResult":{"query":"Letta continual learning in token space memory vs fine-tuning agents","results":[{"tool_use_id":"srvtoolu_01264YtYw67UwqPa9te9PGEA","content":[{"title":"Continual Learning in Token Space | Letta","url":"https://www.letta.com/blog/continual-learning"},{"title":"Skill Learning: Bringing Continual Learning to CLI Agents | Letta","url":"https://www.letta.com/blog/skill-learning"},{"title":"Research | Letta","url":"https://www.letta.com/research/"},{"title":"Letta | Machines that learn","url":"https://www.letta.com/"},{"title":"Letta: Building Stateful AI Agents with In-Context Learning and Memory Management - ZenML LLMOps Database","url":"https://www.zenml.io/llmops-database/building-stateful-ai-agents-with-in-context-learning-and-memory-management"},{"title":"Can Any Model Use Skills? Adding Skills to Context-Bench | Letta","url":"https://www.letta.com/blog/context-bench-skills/"},{"title":"Continual Learning in Token Space: Letta's Research Focus","url":"https://www.linkedin.com/posts/charles-packer_continual-learning-in-token-space-letta-activity-7404985233164496896-kNmI"},{"title":"GitHub - letta-ai/learning-sdk: Drop-in SDK for adding continual learning and long-term memory to any LLM agent. · GitHub","url":"https://github.com/letta-ai/learning-sdk"}]},"Based on the search results, I found comprehensive information about Letta's approach to continual learning in token space compared to fine-tuning approaches:\n\n## Key Differences\n\nRather than just appending to context until it overflows, agents should actively maintain and refine learned memories stored in tokens.\n\n### Challenges with Fine-Tuning Approaches\n\nThe same techniques that make LLM training successful don't transfer to the continual learning setting, as pre, mid, and post-training require meticulous data curation and careful human oversight—a process infeasible to repeat each time an agent needs to learn something new. Additionally, efficient methods like LoRA are still designed for an offline setting with offline evals rather than continual online updates, and leave unanswered questions about learning signals, weighing recent information against older knowledge, and preventing catastrophic forgetting.\n\n### Token Space Learning Advantages\n\nSkill Learning enables agents to learn and improve over time, without needing to change their underlying weights. Unlike fine-tuning or retraining, skills can be created, tested, and deployed immediately—agents acquire new capabilities in real-time as skills become available and can shed skills when no longer needed.\n\n### Real-World Performance\n\nAgents with persistent memory can achieve performance comparable to fine-tuned models while remaining flexible and debuggable.\n\nAgents that can carry their memories across model generations will outlast any single foundation model."],"durationSeconds":7.971345750000007,"searchCount":1},"sourceToolAssistantUUID":"b404bcab-3cf1-42b3-a0a2-d6bc7edabe9b","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main"}
{"parentUuid":"bd4daf56-eb16-46c5-b8d9-cf3b5bd7db44","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"ed988829-c186-4cf7-8fda-2a36bf7006f0","agentId":"a0c75e73218e5c8e8","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01PPz8b1b9TX2SufGsYffehE","type":"tool_result","content":"Web search results for query: \"LoCoMo LongMemEval memory agent benchmark results Mem0 retrieval accuracy\"\n\nLinks: [{\"title\":\"Memory Evaluation - Mem0\",\"url\":\"https://docs.mem0.ai/core-concepts/memory-evaluation\"},{\"title\":\"Benchmarked OpenAI Memory vs LangMem vs MemGPT vs Mem0 for Long-Term Memory - Here’s How They Stacked Up\",\"url\":\"https://mem0.ai/blog/benchmarked-openai-memory-vs-langmem-vs-memgpt-vs-mem0-for-long-term-memory-here-s-how-they-stacked-up\"},{\"title\":\"Introducing The Token-Efficient Memory Algorithm\",\"url\":\"https://mem0.ai/blog/mem0-the-token-efficient-memory-algorithm\"},{\"title\":\"Mem0 Research Paper: Token-Efficient Memory Algorithm\",\"url\":\"https://mem0.ai/research\"},{\"title\":\"AI Memory Benchmarks 2026: LoCoMo, LongMemEval & BEAM\",\"url\":\"https://mem0.ai/blog/ai-memory-benchmarks-in-2026\"},{\"title\":\"AI Memory Research: 26% Accuracy Boost for LLMs\",\"url\":\"https://mem0.ai/research-2\"},{\"title\":\"State of AI Agent Memory 2026: Benchmarks, Architectures & Production Gaps\",\"url\":\"https://mem0.ai/blog/state-of-ai-agent-memory-2026\"},{\"title\":\"Hindsight is 20/20: Building Agent Memory that Retains, Recalls, and Reflects\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2512.12818\"},{\"title\":\"SuperLocalMemory V3: Information-Geometric Foundations for Zero-LLM Enterprise Agent Memory\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2603.14588\"},{\"title\":\"GitHub - mem0ai/memory-benchmarks: Open-source evaluation suite for memory-augmented LLM systems · GitHub\",\"url\":\"https://github.com/mem0ai/memory-benchmarks\"}]\n\nBased on the search results, here are the key benchmark results for Mem0's memory agent performance on LoCoMo and LongMemEval:\n\n## Benchmark Results\n\nMem0's new token-efficient memory algorithm achieves 92.5 on LoCoMo, 94.4 on LongMemEval, and 64.1/48.6 on BEAM (1M/10M) while averaging under 7,000 tokens per retrieval call.\n\n## Performance Improvements\n\nThe two biggest gains are on temporal queries (+29.6) and multi-hop reasoning (+23.1) on the LoCoMo benchmark. For LongMemEval, the biggest gains are on single-session assistant (+53.6), temporal reasoning (+42.1), and knowledge updates (+16.7).\n\n## Token Efficiency\n\nA key distinction of Mem0's approach is its efficiency. The new Mem0 algorithm achieves competitive accuracy on LoCoMo, LongMemEval, and BEAM while averaging under 7,000 tokens per retrieval call, whereas full-context approaches on the same benchmarks routinely consume 25,000+ tokens per query.\n\nThe results demonstrate strong retrieval accuracy across both benchmarks with substantially lower token consumption compared to alternative approaches.\n\n\nREMINDER: You MUST include the sources above in your response to the user using markdown hyperlinks."}]},"uuid":"606254a6-6c0d-4cca-a708-8e1f2198559e","timestamp":"2026-06-21T03:50:10.820Z","toolUseResult":{"query":"LoCoMo LongMemEval memory agent benchmark results Mem0 retrieval accuracy","results":[{"tool_use_id":"srvtoolu_01DPz2UEQq5c2B9RR1HECBMU","content":[{"title":"Memory Evaluation - Mem0","url":"https://docs.mem0.ai/core-concepts/memory-evaluation"},{"title":"Benchmarked OpenAI Memory vs LangMem vs MemGPT vs Mem0 for Long-Term Memory - Here’s How They Stacked Up","url":"https://mem0.ai/blog/benchmarked-openai-memory-vs-langmem-vs-memgpt-vs-mem0-for-long-term-memory-here-s-how-they-stacked-up"},{"title":"Introducing The Token-Efficient Memory Algorithm","url":"https://mem0.ai/blog/mem0-the-token-efficient-memory-algorithm"},{"title":"Mem0 Research Paper: Token-Efficient Memory Algorithm","url":"https://mem0.ai/research"},{"title":"AI Memory Benchmarks 2026: LoCoMo, LongMemEval & BEAM","url":"https://mem0.ai/blog/ai-memory-benchmarks-in-2026"},{"title":"AI Memory Research: 26% Accuracy Boost for LLMs","url":"https://mem0.ai/research-2"},{"title":"State of AI Agent Memory 2026: Benchmarks, Architectures & Production Gaps","url":"https://mem0.ai/blog/state-of-ai-agent-memory-2026"},{"title":"Hindsight is 20/20: Building Agent Memory that Retains, Recalls, and Reflects","url":"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2512.12818"},{"title":"SuperLocalMemory V3: Information-Geometric Foundations for Zero-LLM Enterprise Agent Memory","url":"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2603.14588"},{"title":"GitHub - mem0ai/memory-benchmarks: Open-source evaluation suite for memory-augmented LLM systems · GitHub","url":"https://github.com/mem0ai/memory-benchmarks"}]},"Based on the search results, here are the key benchmark results for Mem0's memory agent performance on LoCoMo and LongMemEval:\n\n## Benchmark Results\n\nMem0's new token-efficient memory algorithm achieves 92.5 on LoCoMo, 94.4 on LongMemEval, and 64.1/48.6 on BEAM (1M/10M) while averaging under 7,000 tokens per retrieval call.\n\n## Performance Improvements\n\nThe two biggest gains are on temporal queries (+29.6) and multi-hop reasoning (+23.1) on the LoCoMo benchmark. For LongMemEval, the biggest gains are on single-session assistant (+53.6), temporal reasoning (+42.1), and knowledge updates (+16.7).\n\n## Token Efficiency\n\nA key distinction of Mem0's approach is its efficiency. The new Mem0 algorithm achieves competitive accuracy on LoCoMo, LongMemEval, and BEAM while averaging under 7,000 tokens per retrieval call, whereas full-context approaches on the same benchmarks routinely consume 25,000+ tokens per query.\n\nThe results demonstrate strong retrieval accuracy across both benchmarks with substantially lower token consumption compared to alternative approaches."],"durationSeconds":9.143762875000014,"searchCount":1},"sourceToolAssistantUUID":"bd4daf56-eb16-46c5-b8d9-cf3b5bd7db44","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main"}
{"parentUuid":"2a39e632-15a6-4316-a876-7d46ffae3eef","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"ed988829-c186-4cf7-8fda-2a36bf7006f0","agentId":"a0c75e73218e5c8e8","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01H3c1H65PtW5tW88wp4oQBe","type":"tool_result","content":"Web search results for query: \"nomic-embed-text embedding dimension cosine similarity hybrid BM25 RAG\"\n\nLinks: [{\"title\":\"nomic-ai/nomic-embed-text-v2-moe · Hugging Face\",\"url\":\"https://huggingface.co/nomic-ai/nomic-embed-text-v2-moe\"},{\"title\":\"Embeddings - OnyxLab | AI/ML Engineering\",\"url\":\"https://www.onyxlab.ai/docs/getting-started/embeddings\"},{\"title\":\"RAG Over PDFs with Nomic Embed Multimodal | Nomic Platform Documentation\",\"url\":\"https://docs.nomic.ai/atlas/embeddings-and-retrieval/guides/pdf-rag-with-nomic-embed-multimodal\"},{\"title\":\"Do You Know What You Are Talking About? Characterizing Query-Knowledge   Relevance For Reliable Retrieval Augmented Generation\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2410.08320\"},{\"title\":\"NV-Embed vs BGE-M3 vs Nomic: Picking the Right Embeddings for Pinecone RAG\",\"url\":\"https://ai-marketinglabs.com/lab-experiments/nv-embed-vs-bge-m3-vs-nomic-picking-the-right-embeddings-for-pinecone-rag\"},{\"title\":\"Feature: Knowledgebase RAG System — User-Configured Document Directory with Local Embedding, Hybrid Search & Auto-Retrieval · Issue #844 · NousResearch/hermes-agent\",\"url\":\"https://github.com/NousResearch/hermes-agent/issues/844\"},{\"title\":\"Ask-EDA: A Design Assistant Empowered by LLM, Hybrid RAG and   Abbreviation De-hallucination\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2406.06575\"},{\"title\":\"Nomic Embed: Training a Reproducible Long Context Text Embedder\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/html/2402.01613v2\"},{\"title\":\"vLLM Semantic Router: Signal Driven Decision Routing for Mixture-of-Modality Models\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2603.04444\"}]\n\nThe search results provide relevant information about nomic-embed-text and its use in RAG systems with various retrieval methods. Here's what I found:\n\n## Nomic Embed Text Overview\n\nNomic is a long context-length text encoder that uses dot product as the similarity metric and has an embedding size of 768 for the unsupervised version. Additionally, the v2-moe model supports truncation/Matryoshka embeddings with flexible dimensions, allowing you to specify truncate_dim (such as 256).\n\n## Embedding Dimension and Similarity\n\nFor the original version, nomic-embed-text-v1-unsupervised uses dot product as the similarity metric and has an embedding size of 768. The newer model offers flexibility through Matryoshka representation learning for adjustable dimensions.\n\n## Hybrid Retrieval with BM25 in RAG\n\nHybrid approaches combining dense and sparse embeddings maximize recall and are often the default recommendation for production systems. In hybrid RAG, queries are encoded and matched to dense embeddings with cosine similarity to get top semantically-relevant chunks, while BM25 finds the most-relevant chunks based on a precomputed index, and results are combined with reciprocal rank fusion.\n\n## Performance Benefits\n\nHybrid search improves recall 15-30% over either method alone and is critical for code (requiring exact BM25 matching for variable/function names) and documentation (technical jargon plus conceptual similarity).\n\n\nREMINDER: You MUST include the sources above in your response to the user using markdown hyperlinks."}]},"uuid":"059cbdae-c7fb-494a-9822-1f5504dbd450","timestamp":"2026-06-21T03:50:11.559Z","toolUseResult":{"query":"nomic-embed-text embedding dimension cosine similarity hybrid BM25 RAG","results":[{"tool_use_id":"srvtoolu_013iQfG2STNnQfWCPvHQnuzo","content":[{"title":"nomic-ai/nomic-embed-text-v2-moe · Hugging Face","url":"https://huggingface.co/nomic-ai/nomic-embed-text-v2-moe"},{"title":"Embeddings - OnyxLab | AI/ML Engineering","url":"https://www.onyxlab.ai/docs/getting-started/embeddings"},{"title":"RAG Over PDFs with Nomic Embed Multimodal | Nomic Platform Documentation","url":"https://docs.nomic.ai/atlas/embeddings-and-retrieval/guides/pdf-rag-with-nomic-embed-multimodal"},{"title":"Do You Know What You Are Talking About? Characterizing Query-Knowledge   Relevance For Reliable Retrieval Augmented Generation","url":"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2410.08320"},{"title":"NV-Embed vs BGE-M3 vs Nomic: Picking the Right Embeddings for Pinecone RAG","url":"https://ai-marketinglabs.com/lab-experiments/nv-embed-vs-bge-m3-vs-nomic-picking-the-right-embeddings-for-pinecone-rag"},{"title":"Feature: Knowledgebase RAG System — User-Configured Document Directory with Local Embedding, Hybrid Search & Auto-Retrieval · Issue #844 · NousResearch/hermes-agent","url":"https://github.com/NousResearch/hermes-agent/issues/844"},{"title":"Ask-EDA: A Design Assistant Empowered by LLM, Hybrid RAG and   Abbreviation De-hallucination","url":"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2406.06575"},{"title":"Nomic Embed: Training a Reproducible Long Context Text Embedder","url":"https://arxiv.org/html/2402.01613v2"},{"title":"vLLM Semantic Router: Signal Driven Decision Routing for Mixture-of-Modality Models","url":"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2603.04444"}]},"The search results provide relevant information about nomic-embed-text and its use in RAG systems with various retrieval methods. Here's what I found:\n\n## Nomic Embed Text Overview\n\nNomic is a long context-length text encoder that uses dot product as the similarity metric and has an embedding size of 768 for the unsupervised version. Additionally, the v2-moe model supports truncation/Matryoshka embeddings with flexible dimensions, allowing you to specify truncate_dim (such as 256).\n\n## Embedding Dimension and Similarity\n\nFor the original version, nomic-embed-text-v1-unsupervised uses dot product as the similarity metric and has an embedding size of 768. The newer model offers flexibility through Matryoshka representation learning for adjustable dimensions.\n\n## Hybrid Retrieval with BM25 in RAG\n\nHybrid approaches combining dense and sparse embeddings maximize recall and are often the default recommendation for production systems. In hybrid RAG, queries are encoded and matched to dense embeddings with cosine similarity to get top semantically-relevant chunks, while BM25 finds the most-relevant chunks based on a precomputed index, and results are combined with reciprocal rank fusion.\n\n## Performance Benefits\n\nHybrid search improves recall 15-30% over either method alone and is critical for code (requiring exact BM25 matching for variable/function names) and documentation (technical jargon plus conceptual similarity)."],"durationSeconds":8.549848582999985,"searchCount":1},"sourceToolAssistantUUID":"2a39e632-15a6-4316-a876-7d46ffae3eef","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main"}
{"parentUuid":"0a14a60c-da7b-4b44-94f7-00c2299dfa00","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"ed988829-c186-4cf7-8fda-2a36bf7006f0","agentId":"a0c75e73218e5c8e8","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01Nit6px4dhLMjoxsRRLac4r","type":"tool_result","content":"Web search results for query: \"A-MEM agentic memory episodic semantic consolidation LLM agent performance improvement\"\n\nLinks: [{\"title\":\"A-MEM: Agentic Memory for LLM Agents\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2502.12110\"},{\"title\":\"A-Mem: Agentic Memory for LLM Agents | OpenReview\",\"url\":\"https://openreview.net/forum?id=FiM0M8gcct\"},{\"title\":\"GitHub - agiresearch/A-mem: A-MEM: Agentic Memory for LLM Agents · GitHub\",\"url\":\"https://github.com/agiresearch/a-mem\"},{\"title\":\"Scaling Teams or Scaling Time? Memory Enabled Lifelong Learning in LLM Multi-Agent Systems\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2604.03295\"},{\"title\":\"A-Mem: Agentic Memory for LLM Agents\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/html/2502.12110v1\"},{\"title\":\"A-MEM: Agentic Memory for LLM Agents Anonymous ACL submission Abstract 001\",\"url\":\"https://openreview.net/pdf?id=LB0nTqxAKd\"},{\"title\":\"Amory: Building Coherent Narrative-Driven Agent Memory through Agentic Reasoning\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2601.06282\"}]\n\nThe search returned comprehensive results about A-MEM and related agentic memory systems for LLM agents. Here's what I found:\n\n## A-MEM: Agentic Memory for LLM Agents\n\nA-MEM is a novel agentic memory system for LLM agents that enables dynamic memory structuring without relying on static, predetermined memory operations. The approach draws inspiration from the Zettelkasten method, a sophisticated knowledge management system that creates interconnected information networks through atomic notes and flexible linking mechanisms.\n\n### Key Architecture Components\n\nFor each new memory, the system constructs comprehensive notes that integrate multiple representations: structured textual attributes and embedding vectors for similarity matching. The system leverages an LLM to analyze interactions and generate semantic components, following the Zettelkasten principle of atomicity where each note captures a single, self-contained unit of knowledge.\n\n### Memory Organization and Consolidation\n\nThe A-MEM architecture comprises three integral parts in memory storage: during note construction, the system processes new interaction memories and stores them as notes with multiple attributes, and a link generation process retrieves the most relevant historical memories and decides whether to establish connections between them.\n\n### Performance Improvements\n\nEmpirical experiments conducted on six foundation models demonstrate superior performance compared to existing SOTA baselines. The method outperforms all baseline approaches across all metrics, with the Multi-Hop category showcasing particularly strong results—surpassing previous methods and representing a nearly six-fold improvement.\n\n\nREMINDER: You MUST include the sources above in your response to the user using markdown hyperlinks."}]},"uuid":"3d339d0b-2dc4-4fe7-b8a8-88bea6f8371c","timestamp":"2026-06-21T03:50:12.370Z","toolUseResult":{"query":"A-MEM agentic memory episodic semantic consolidation LLM agent performance improvement","results":[{"tool_use_id":"srvtoolu_01LTnS8PKi1g8B28Nz47WPr8","content":[{"title":"A-MEM: Agentic Memory for LLM Agents","url":"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2502.12110"},{"title":"A-Mem: Agentic Memory for LLM Agents | OpenReview","url":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=FiM0M8gcct"},{"title":"GitHub - agiresearch/A-mem: A-MEM: Agentic Memory for LLM Agents · GitHub","url":"https://github.com/agiresearch/a-mem"},{"title":"Scaling Teams or Scaling Time? Memory Enabled Lifelong Learning in LLM Multi-Agent Systems","url":"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2604.03295"},{"title":"A-Mem: Agentic Memory for LLM Agents","url":"https://arxiv.org/html/2502.12110v1"},{"title":"A-MEM: Agentic Memory for LLM Agents Anonymous ACL submission Abstract 001","url":"https://openreview.net/pdf?id=LB0nTqxAKd"},{"title":"Amory: Building Coherent Narrative-Driven Agent Memory through Agentic Reasoning","url":"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2601.06282"}]},"The search returned comprehensive results about A-MEM and related agentic memory systems for LLM agents. Here's what I found:\n\n## A-MEM: Agentic Memory for LLM Agents\n\nA-MEM is a novel agentic memory system for LLM agents that enables dynamic memory structuring without relying on static, predetermined memory operations. The approach draws inspiration from the Zettelkasten method, a sophisticated knowledge management system that creates interconnected information networks through atomic notes and flexible linking mechanisms.\n\n### Key Architecture Components\n\nFor each new memory, the system constructs comprehensive notes that integrate multiple representations: structured textual attributes and embedding vectors for similarity matching. The system leverages an LLM to analyze interactions and generate semantic components, following the Zettelkasten principle of atomicity where each note captures a single, self-contained unit of knowledge.\n\n### Memory Organization and Consolidation\n\nThe A-MEM architecture comprises three integral parts in memory storage: during note construction, the system processes new interaction memories and stores them as notes with multiple attributes, and a link generation process retrieves the most relevant historical memories and decides whether to establish connections between them.\n\n### Performance Improvements\n\nEmpirical experiments conducted on six foundation models demonstrate superior performance compared to existing SOTA baselines. The method outperforms all baseline approaches across all metrics, with the Multi-Hop category showcasing particularly strong results—surpassing previous methods and representing a nearly six-fold improvement."],"durationSeconds":9.720432,"searchCount":1},"sourceToolAssistantUUID":"0a14a60c-da7b-4b44-94f7-00c2299dfa00","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main"}
