{"parentUuid":"7a0387e3-cbad-4dbb-9705-a751f56a9ee5","isSidechain":true,"agentId":"a0c75e73218e5c8e8","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-8","id":"msg_01KwN2eGpCbGuuQCeckFCKKQ","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01LwNzifDtXxSosKQyYNRJq6","name":"WebFetch","input":{"url":"https://mem0.ai/blog/ai-memory-benchmarks-in-2026","prompt":"Summarize the LoCoMo, LongMemEval and BEAM benchmarks: what do they measure, what is the baseline (no memory / full context), and what improvement does memory provide vs no memory? Give concrete numbers attributable to memory vs none. Note any limitations or criticisms of these benchmarks."},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1306,"cache_creation_input_tokens":4613,"cache_read_input_tokens":12519,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":4613,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"output_tokens":3,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null},"requestId":"req_011CcFivuqzHCkUdNJwKJaSe","attributionAgent":"general-purpose","type":"assistant","uuid":"fdcf7bb6-258b-4092-b438-31d795f1ea9a","timestamp":"2026-06-21T03:50:20.905Z","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main"}
{"parentUuid":"fdcf7bb6-258b-4092-b438-31d795f1ea9a","isSidechain":true,"agentId":"a0c75e73218e5c8e8","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-8","id":"msg_01KwN2eGpCbGuuQCeckFCKKQ","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01VhXo4YB3EZQ2hKAZNUfBeS","name":"WebSearch","input":{"query":"RAG retrieval failure modes stale memory drift recency freshness weighting time decay vector search"},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":"tool_use","stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1306,"cache_creation_input_tokens":4613,"cache_read_input_tokens":12519,"output_tokens":503,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":4613},"inference_geo":"not_available","iterations":[{"input_tokens":1306,"output_tokens":503,"cache_read_input_tokens":12519,"cache_creation_input_tokens":4613,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":4613,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"type":"message"}],"speed":"standard"},"diagnostics":null},"requestId":"req_011CcFivuqzHCkUdNJwKJaSe","attributionAgent":"general-purpose","type":"assistant","uuid":"6fd498df-fb41-49e1-8382-17421bde8e6d","timestamp":"2026-06-21T03:50:21.382Z","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main"}
{"parentUuid":"7a0387e3-cbad-4dbb-9705-a751f56a9ee5","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"ed988829-c186-4cf7-8fda-2a36bf7006f0","agentId":"a0c75e73218e5c8e8","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01M9zEupjYYcYkxjzE6p6D4s","type":"tool_result","content":"# Continual Learning in Token Space: Argument Summary\n\n## Core Argument\n\nRather than updating frozen model weights through fine-tuning, Letta proposes learning happens primarily through updating the *context* that conditions model behavior—system prompts, tool definitions, conversation history, and accumulated experience.\n\n## Key Advantages Over Weight Training\n\nToken-space learning addresses three critical problems with traditional continual learning:\n\n1. **Interpretability**: \"Token-space memories are human-readable. You can inspect what an agent has learned, evaluate whether it's correct, and debug failures directly.\"\n\n2. **Portability**: \"An agent's learned context can transfer across agents, model providers, and even across model generations.\"\n\n3. **Reversibility**: \"Forgetting is trivial: just delete the tokens\" and \"learned context can be checkpointed and versioned like any text file.\"\n\n## Proposed Mechanisms\n\nThe paper identifies three approaches but remains largely **conceptual rather than empirical**:\n\n- **Sleep-time compute**: Background processing to consolidate memories, identify contradictions, and abstract patterns\n- **Agent self-awareness**: Training models to recognize memory degradation and actively restructure context\n- **Distillation**: Eventually converting token-based memories into model weights for efficiency\n\n## Critical Gap\n\n**The paper makes no evidence-based claims about measurable improvement.** It presents no experiments showing token-space learning compounds benefits with frozen models. The work is primarily a theoretical reframing and research agenda, not empirical validation."}]},"uuid":"94c61fbe-7526-4615-8139-19a4c4d24c9c","timestamp":"2026-06-21T03:50:24.253Z","toolUseResult":{"bytes":75673,"code":200,"codeText":"OK","result":"# Continual Learning in Token Space: Argument Summary\n\n## Core Argument\n\nRather than updating frozen model weights through fine-tuning, Letta proposes learning happens primarily through updating the *context* that conditions model behavior—system prompts, tool definitions, conversation history, and accumulated experience.\n\n## Key Advantages Over Weight Training\n\nToken-space learning addresses three critical problems with traditional continual learning:\n\n1. **Interpretability**: \"Token-space memories are human-readable. You can inspect what an agent has learned, evaluate whether it's correct, and debug failures directly.\"\n\n2. **Portability**: \"An agent's learned context can transfer across agents, model providers, and even across model generations.\"\n\n3. **Reversibility**: \"Forgetting is trivial: just delete the tokens\" and \"learned context can be checkpointed and versioned like any text file.\"\n\n## Proposed Mechanisms\n\nThe paper identifies three approaches but remains largely **conceptual rather than empirical**:\n\n- **Sleep-time compute**: Background processing to consolidate memories, identify contradictions, and abstract patterns\n- **Agent self-awareness**: Training models to recognize memory degradation and actively restructure context\n- **Distillation**: Eventually converting token-based memories into model weights for efficiency\n\n## Critical Gap\n\n**The paper makes no evidence-based claims about measurable improvement.** It presents no experiments showing token-space learning compounds benefits with frozen models. The work is primarily a theoretical reframing and research agenda, not empirical validation.","durationMs":5389,"url":"https://www.letta.com/blog/continual-learning"},"sourceToolAssistantUUID":"7a0387e3-cbad-4dbb-9705-a751f56a9ee5","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main"}
{"parentUuid":"fdcf7bb6-258b-4092-b438-31d795f1ea9a","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"ed988829-c186-4cf7-8fda-2a36bf7006f0","agentId":"a0c75e73218e5c8e8","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01LwNzifDtXxSosKQyYNRJq6","type":"tool_result","content":"# AI Memory Benchmarks Summary\n\n## LoCoMo (2024)\n**What it measures:** Cross-session continuity across very long conversations (averaging 300 turns, 9,000 tokens, up to 35 sessions) with QA, event summarization, and timeline ordering tasks.\n\n**Baseline:** Long-context LLMs and retrieval-augmented setups tested against human performance.\n\n**Key finding:** Models \"still substantially lag behind human performance\" on these extended multi-session conversations.\n\n**Limitations:** Modest context length by 2026 standards; doesn't explicitly score knowledge updates.\n\n---\n\n## LongMemEval (2024)\n**What it measures:** Five memory abilities—information extraction, multi-session reasoning, temporal reasoning, knowledge updates, and abstention (declining to answer on non-existent events).\n\n**Scale:** Two versions with 115K tokens (40 sessions) and 500 sessions per user; 500 curated questions total.\n\n**Baseline:** Commercial assistants and long-context LLMs show a \"30% accuracy drop\" on multi-session memory tasks.\n\n**Limitations:** Abstention testing is novel but benchmarks still focus primarily on retrieval rather than write quality.\n\n---\n\n## BEAM (2026)\n**What it measures:** Ten memory capabilities across million-token and 10-million-token contexts with 2,000 probing questions per conversation.\n\n**Baseline:** Long-context models alone; the benchmark demonstrates that \"long context alone\" cannot saturate it.\n\n**Memory advantage:** Structured memory frameworks achieved \"3.5% to 12.7% higher accuracy\" versus strongest long-context baselines, widening at larger scales.\n\n**Key limitation:** No production-scale benchmarks yet test per-user isolation, write quality, or forgetting dynamics."}]},"uuid":"da9528de-7c63-4fb7-bcc2-dc0de75611e4","timestamp":"2026-06-21T03:50:30.010Z","toolUseResult":{"bytes":18274,"code":200,"codeText":"OK","result":"# AI Memory Benchmarks Summary\n\n## LoCoMo (2024)\n**What it measures:** Cross-session continuity across very long conversations (averaging 300 turns, 9,000 tokens, up to 35 sessions) with QA, event summarization, and timeline ordering tasks.\n\n**Baseline:** Long-context LLMs and retrieval-augmented setups tested against human performance.\n\n**Key finding:** Models \"still substantially lag behind human performance\" on these extended multi-session conversations.\n\n**Limitations:** Modest context length by 2026 standards; doesn't explicitly score knowledge updates.\n\n---\n\n## LongMemEval (2024)\n**What it measures:** Five memory abilities—information extraction, multi-session reasoning, temporal reasoning, knowledge updates, and abstention (declining to answer on non-existent events).\n\n**Scale:** Two versions with 115K tokens (40 sessions) and 500 sessions per user; 500 curated questions total.\n\n**Baseline:** Commercial assistants and long-context LLMs show a \"30% accuracy drop\" on multi-session memory tasks.\n\n**Limitations:** Abstention testing is novel but benchmarks still focus primarily on retrieval rather than write quality.\n\n---\n\n## BEAM (2026)\n**What it measures:** Ten memory capabilities across million-token and 10-million-token contexts with 2,000 probing questions per conversation.\n\n**Baseline:** Long-context models alone; the benchmark demonstrates that \"long context alone\" cannot saturate it.\n\n**Memory advantage:** Structured memory frameworks achieved \"3.5% to 12.7% higher accuracy\" versus strongest long-context baselines, widening at larger scales.\n\n**Key limitation:** No production-scale benchmarks yet test per-user isolation, write quality, or forgetting dynamics.","durationMs":8876,"url":"https://mem0.ai/blog/ai-memory-benchmarks-in-2026"},"sourceToolAssistantUUID":"fdcf7bb6-258b-4092-b438-31d795f1ea9a","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main"}
{"parentUuid":"6fd498df-fb41-49e1-8382-17421bde8e6d","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"ed988829-c186-4cf7-8fda-2a36bf7006f0","agentId":"a0c75e73218e5c8e8","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01VhXo4YB3EZQ2hKAZNUfBeS","type":"tool_result","content":"Web search results for query: \"RAG retrieval failure modes stale memory drift recency freshness weighting time decay vector search\"\n\nLinks: [{\"title\":\"10 RAG Failure Modes at Scale (and How to Fix Them) | by Bhagya Rana | Medium\",\"url\":\"https://medium.com/@bhagyarana80/10-rag-failure-modes-at-scale-and-how-to-fix-them-158240ce3a05\"},{\"title\":\"Solving Freshness in RAG: A Simple Recency Prior and the Limits\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2509.19376\"},{\"title\":\"(PDF) Solving Freshness in RAG: A Simple Recency Prior and the Limits of Heuristic Trend Detection\",\"url\":\"https://www.researchgate.net/publication/395806121_Solving_Freshness_in_RAG_A_Simple_Recency_Prior_and_the_Limits_of_Heuristic_Trend_Detection\"},{\"title\":\"Solving Freshness in RAG: A Simple Recency Prior and the Limits of Heuristic Trend Detection\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/html/2509.19376\"},{\"title\":\"Your RAG Gets Confidently Wrong as Memory Grows – I Built the Memory Layer That Stops It | Towards Data Science\",\"url\":\"https://towardsdatascience.com/your-rag-gets-confidently-wrong-as-memory-grows-i-built-the-memory-layer-that-stops-it/\"},{\"title\":\"Data freshness rot as the silent failure mode in production RAG systems, and treating document shelf life as a first-class reliability concern - Glen Rhodes\",\"url\":\"https://glenrhodes.com/data-freshness-rot-as-the-silent-failure-mode-in-production-rag-systems-and-treating-document-shelf-life-as-a-first-class-reliability-concern/\"},{\"title\":\"Ten Failure Modes of RAG Nobody Talks About (And How to Detect Them Systematically) - DEV Community\",\"url\":\"https://dev.to/kuldeep_paul/ten-failure-modes-of-rag-nobody-talks-about-and-how-to-detect-them-systematically-7i4\"},{\"title\":\"The RAG Freshness Problem: How Stale Embeddings Silently Wreck Retrieval Quality - TianPan.co\",\"url\":\"https://tianpan.co/blog/2026-04-10-rag-freshness-problem-stale-embeddings-silent-failure\"}]\n\nI've completed the web search for your query on RAG retrieval failure modes related to stale memory, drift, recency, freshness, weighting, time decay, and vector search. Here's a summary of the key findings:\n\n## Major RAG Failure Modes\n\nProduction RAG breaks in predictable ways including drift, stale indexes, bad chunking, reranker bugs, and context overload.\n\n## Freshness and Staleness Issues\n\nWithout a temporal component, retrieval pipelines risk elevating stale or misleading information, and systems that retrieve only cosine similarity will surface stale context or fail to distinguish novel updates from redundant information. Outdated documents still score high on semantic similarity, so the retriever has no idea they're stale.\n\n## Recency Weighting Solutions\n\nAugmenting embeddings using a practical, time-aware scoring method that fuses content similarity with recency weighting has been proposed as a solution. A small, explicit temporal prior fixes a large fraction of these failure modes in practice.\n\n## Memory Drift and Scaling Issues\n\nCosine similarity measures coherence not correctness, FIFO eviction discards relevant old entries, and stale entries accumulate collective weight. Production data shows retrieval recall degrading from 0.92 to 0.74 over time, with previously top-ranked relevant documents drifting from position 2 to position 8.\n\n## Topic Drift\n\nA half-life prior guards against stale facts and weekly clusters expose topic drift as a story reframes over time.\n\nThe search results contain substantial research on these topics from recent academic papers and practical production systems.\n\n\nREMINDER: You MUST include the sources above in your response to the user using markdown hyperlinks."}]},"uuid":"55db432f-8daf-4a01-bff5-b8ec7e0dbf15","timestamp":"2026-06-21T03:50:31.161Z","toolUseResult":{"query":"RAG retrieval failure modes stale memory drift recency freshness weighting time decay vector search","results":[{"tool_use_id":"srvtoolu_01R3hX94ptrRPbCrsQhBqXfm","content":[{"title":"10 RAG Failure Modes at Scale (and How to Fix Them) | by Bhagya Rana | Medium","url":"https://medium.com/@bhagyarana80/10-rag-failure-modes-at-scale-and-how-to-fix-them-158240ce3a05"},{"title":"Solving Freshness in RAG: A Simple Recency Prior and the Limits","url":"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2509.19376"},{"title":"(PDF) Solving Freshness in RAG: A Simple Recency Prior and the Limits of Heuristic Trend Detection","url":"https://www.researchgate.net/publication/395806121_Solving_Freshness_in_RAG_A_Simple_Recency_Prior_and_the_Limits_of_Heuristic_Trend_Detection"},{"title":"Solving Freshness in RAG: A Simple Recency Prior and the Limits of Heuristic Trend Detection","url":"https://arxiv.org/html/2509.19376"},{"title":"Your RAG Gets Confidently Wrong as Memory Grows – I Built the Memory Layer That Stops It | Towards Data Science","url":"https://towardsdatascience.com/your-rag-gets-confidently-wrong-as-memory-grows-i-built-the-memory-layer-that-stops-it/"},{"title":"Data freshness rot as the silent failure mode in production RAG systems, and treating document shelf life as a first-class reliability concern - Glen Rhodes","url":"https://glenrhodes.com/data-freshness-rot-as-the-silent-failure-mode-in-production-rag-systems-and-treating-document-shelf-life-as-a-first-class-reliability-concern/"},{"title":"Ten Failure Modes of RAG Nobody Talks About (And How to Detect Them Systematically) - DEV Community","url":"https://dev.to/kuldeep_paul/ten-failure-modes-of-rag-nobody-talks-about-and-how-to-detect-them-systematically-7i4"},{"title":"The RAG Freshness Problem: How Stale Embeddings Silently Wreck Retrieval Quality - TianPan.co","url":"https://tianpan.co/blog/2026-04-10-rag-freshness-problem-stale-embeddings-silent-failure"}]},"I've completed the web search for your query on RAG retrieval failure modes related to stale memory, drift, recency, freshness, weighting, time decay, and vector search. Here's a summary of the key findings:\n\n## Major RAG Failure Modes\n\nProduction RAG breaks in predictable ways including drift, stale indexes, bad chunking, reranker bugs, and context overload.\n\n## Freshness and Staleness Issues\n\nWithout a temporal component, retrieval pipelines risk elevating stale or misleading information, and systems that retrieve only cosine similarity will surface stale context or fail to distinguish novel updates from redundant information. Outdated documents still score high on semantic similarity, so the retriever has no idea they're stale.\n\n## Recency Weighting Solutions\n\nAugmenting embeddings using a practical, time-aware scoring method that fuses content similarity with recency weighting has been proposed as a solution. A small, explicit temporal prior fixes a large fraction of these failure modes in practice.\n\n## Memory Drift and Scaling Issues\n\nCosine similarity measures coherence not correctness, FIFO eviction discards relevant old entries, and stale entries accumulate collective weight. Production data shows retrieval recall degrading from 0.92 to 0.74 over time, with previously top-ranked relevant documents drifting from position 2 to position 8.\n\n## Topic Drift\n\nA half-life prior guards against stale facts and weekly clusters expose topic drift as a story reframes over time.\n\nThe search results contain substantial research on these topics from recent academic papers and practical production systems."],"durationSeconds":9.558572208999976,"searchCount":1},"sourceToolAssistantUUID":"6fd498df-fb41-49e1-8382-17421bde8e6d","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main"}
