{"parentUuid":"8ca2869f-baff-4e81-8e1b-6f48692ca76a","isSidechain":true,"agentId":"a0c75e73218e5c8e8","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-8","id":"msg_01LEtgz398gWXbq4gduVFMEK","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01CgVCwRivYHoYNjarBBLkCT","name":"WebFetch","input":{"url":"https://arxiv.org/html/2509.19376","prompt":"Describe the recency prior / time-aware scoring method for RAG freshness. What is the exact formula for fusing cosine similarity with recency weighting (e.g. half-life / exponential decay)? What are the limits of heuristic recency? Give practical parameters."},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":"tool_use","stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":325,"cache_creation_input_tokens":4403,"cache_read_input_tokens":17132,"output_tokens":565,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":4403},"inference_geo":"not_available","iterations":[{"input_tokens":325,"output_tokens":565,"cache_read_input_tokens":17132,"cache_creation_input_tokens":4403,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":4403,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"type":"message"}],"speed":"standard"},"diagnostics":null},"requestId":"req_011CcFixJ3FdjRLLBNhosSjr","attributionAgent":"general-purpose","type":"assistant","uuid":"ecb3e0f4-548e-43ec-844a-d2a16e6fd7ef","timestamp":"2026-06-21T03:50:39.470Z","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main"}
{"parentUuid":"3f80c95f-9a5b-49c4-9418-242f8618396f","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"ed988829-c186-4cf7-8fda-2a36bf7006f0","agentId":"a0c75e73218e5c8e8","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01DrRJemtEiwHqH3bmS7yP6U","type":"tool_result","content":"# Skill Learning Overview\n\n**What It Is:**\nSkill Learning is a system enabling agents to dynamically acquire and improve capabilities over time without modifying underlying model weights. It operates through a two-stage process: reflection (analyzing task trajectories to identify patterns and failures) and creation (generating structured skill files).\n\n**Empirical Evidence:**\nThe research demonstrates quantified performance improvements on Terminal Bench 2.0:\n- Skills from trajectories alone: \"21.1% relative (9% absolute) increase\" in performance\n- Skills enhanced with error feedback: \"36.8% relative (15.7% absolute)\" improvement over baseline\n- Additional benefits include 15.7% cost reduction and 10.4% fewer tool calls\n\n**How Skills Work:**\nSkills are stored as markdown files designed for modularity and version control compatibility. The system uses Anthropic's skill-creator tool to generate files containing \"potential approaches, common pitfalls, and verification strategies.\" Agents access skills dynamically during task execution through the Letta Code harness using the `/skill` command.\n\n**Key Innovation:**\nUnlike static skill libraries, this approach enables \"agents to learn and improve over time\" by capturing domain-specific knowledge from failed and successful task attempts, particularly when supplemented with verifier feedback indicating error patterns."}]},"uuid":"024056a1-8fe0-4b1f-9c15-e3f93351b9a8","timestamp":"2026-06-21T03:50:40.940Z","toolUseResult":{"bytes":30727,"code":200,"codeText":"OK","result":"# Skill Learning Overview\n\n**What It Is:**\nSkill Learning is a system enabling agents to dynamically acquire and improve capabilities over time without modifying underlying model weights. It operates through a two-stage process: reflection (analyzing task trajectories to identify patterns and failures) and creation (generating structured skill files).\n\n**Empirical Evidence:**\nThe research demonstrates quantified performance improvements on Terminal Bench 2.0:\n- Skills from trajectories alone: \"21.1% relative (9% absolute) increase\" in performance\n- Skills enhanced with error feedback: \"36.8% relative (15.7% absolute)\" improvement over baseline\n- Additional benefits include 15.7% cost reduction and 10.4% fewer tool calls\n\n**How Skills Work:**\nSkills are stored as markdown files designed for modularity and version control compatibility. The system uses Anthropic's skill-creator tool to generate files containing \"potential approaches, common pitfalls, and verification strategies.\" Agents access skills dynamically during task execution through the Letta Code harness using the `/skill` command.\n\n**Key Innovation:**\nUnlike static skill libraries, this approach enables \"agents to learn and improve over time\" by capturing domain-specific knowledge from failed and successful task attempts, particularly when supplemented with verifier feedback indicating error patterns.","durationMs":4522,"url":"https://www.letta.com/blog/skill-learning"},"sourceToolAssistantUUID":"3f80c95f-9a5b-49c4-9418-242f8618396f","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main"}
{"parentUuid":"8ca2869f-baff-4e81-8e1b-6f48692ca76a","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"ed988829-c186-4cf7-8fda-2a36bf7006f0","agentId":"a0c75e73218e5c8e8","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01Uz2bScY8XmqWPGtoY3PqC2","type":"tool_result","content":"# Mem0 Research Results: What the Paper Shows\n\n## Accuracy Results on LoCoMo\nThe research demonstrates a **92.5% overall score on LoCoMo** across 1,540 questions spanning 5 categories (single-hop, multi-hop, open-domain, temporal, and old/new information).\n\n## Token Efficiency vs. Full-Context Approaches\nThe key efficiency claim: Mem0 achieves its results while using **under 7,000 tokens per retrieval call** (specifically 6,956 mean tokens on LoCoMo). By contrast, the paper states that **\"full-context approaches on these benchmarks routinely consume 25,000+ tokens per query\"** — representing approximately 3-4x token savings.\n\n## Additional Benchmark Performance\n- **LongMemEval**: 94.4% accuracy with 6,787 mean tokens\n- **BEAM 1M**: 64.1% accuracy with 6,719 mean tokens  \n- **BEAM 10M**: 48.6% accuracy with 6,914 mean tokens\n\n## Notable Limitation\nThe webpage does **not provide comparative numbers** against specific baselines like RAG, MemGPT/Letta, OpenAI memory, or no-memory baselines. It only contrasts against generic \"full-context approaches\" without naming competitors or providing their specific accuracy/token metrics.\n\nThe paper emphasizes architectural innovations (single-pass extraction, multi-signal retrieval) but quantifies improvement primarily through absolute accuracy scores rather than direct comparative analysis."}]},"uuid":"e0154412-9e50-48ac-89fd-85da4d7d6cd6","timestamp":"2026-06-21T03:50:43.732Z","toolUseResult":{"bytes":3672,"code":200,"codeText":"OK","result":"# Mem0 Research Results: What the Paper Shows\n\n## Accuracy Results on LoCoMo\nThe research demonstrates a **92.5% overall score on LoCoMo** across 1,540 questions spanning 5 categories (single-hop, multi-hop, open-domain, temporal, and old/new information).\n\n## Token Efficiency vs. Full-Context Approaches\nThe key efficiency claim: Mem0 achieves its results while using **under 7,000 tokens per retrieval call** (specifically 6,956 mean tokens on LoCoMo). By contrast, the paper states that **\"full-context approaches on these benchmarks routinely consume 25,000+ tokens per query\"** — representing approximately 3-4x token savings.\n\n## Additional Benchmark Performance\n- **LongMemEval**: 94.4% accuracy with 6,787 mean tokens\n- **BEAM 1M**: 64.1% accuracy with 6,719 mean tokens  \n- **BEAM 10M**: 48.6% accuracy with 6,914 mean tokens\n\n## Notable Limitation\nThe webpage does **not provide comparative numbers** against specific baselines like RAG, MemGPT/Letta, OpenAI memory, or no-memory baselines. It only contrasts against generic \"full-context approaches\" without naming competitors or providing their specific accuracy/token metrics.\n\nThe paper emphasizes architectural innovations (single-pass extraction, multi-signal retrieval) but quantifies improvement primarily through absolute accuracy scores rather than direct comparative analysis.","durationMs":5363,"url":"https://mem0.ai/research"},"sourceToolAssistantUUID":"8ca2869f-baff-4e81-8e1b-6f48692ca76a","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main"}
{"parentUuid":"ecb3e0f4-548e-43ec-844a-d2a16e6fd7ef","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"ed988829-c186-4cf7-8fda-2a36bf7006f0","agentId":"a0c75e73218e5c8e8","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01CgVCwRivYHoYNjarBBLkCT","type":"tool_result","content":"# Recency Prior for RAG Freshness\n\n## Core Formula\n\nThe paper implements a fused scoring mechanism combining semantic and temporal signals:\n\n```\nscore(q,d,t) = α·cos(q,d) + (1−α)·0.5^(age_days(t)/h)\n```\n\nWhere:\n- **α** = weighting parameter (default 0.7) balancing semantic vs. recency\n- **cos(q,d)** = cosine similarity between query and document embeddings\n- **age_days(t)** = days elapsed since document timestamp\n- **h** = half-life in days (default 14 days)\n\nThe exponential decay component ensures older documents gradually become less relevant, with importance halving every `h` days.\n\n## Practical Parameters\n\n| Parameter | Default | Use Case |\n|-----------|---------|----------|\n| α (alpha) | 0.7 | Balanced semantic-temporal weighting |\n| Half-life (h) | 14 days | Enterprise information lifecycle |\n| Query scope | 7 days | Freshness-focused retrieval |\n\nThe authors note α values of 0.4–0.7 maintain perfect accuracy; values ≥0.9 degrade to 66.7% as semantic similarity dominates.\n\n## Limits of Heuristic Approaches\n\nThe paper reveals critical failures in simple heuristic trend detection. Their K-means clustering baseline achieved only 0.08 F1-score for identifying topic dynamics (growth/drift/decay). Key limitations:\n\n- **Fixed K assumption**: Real-world data showed unstable optimal clusters (K=3 to K=9 weekly)\n- **Spherical clusters**: Semantic topics are often non-convex, violating K-means assumptions\n- **High dimensionality**: The 384-dimensional embedding space makes Euclidean distance less meaningful\n\nThe authors conclude that basic freshness is tractable, but nuanced topic evolution remains an open challenge requiring probabilistic methods like Dynamic Topic Models."}]},"uuid":"d9cb423d-19f5-4586-87b3-a6f81e429649","timestamp":"2026-06-21T03:50:46.636Z","toolUseResult":{"bytes":108225,"code":200,"codeText":"OK","result":"# Recency Prior for RAG Freshness\n\n## Core Formula\n\nThe paper implements a fused scoring mechanism combining semantic and temporal signals:\n\n```\nscore(q,d,t) = α·cos(q,d) + (1−α)·0.5^(age_days(t)/h)\n```\n\nWhere:\n- **α** = weighting parameter (default 0.7) balancing semantic vs. recency\n- **cos(q,d)** = cosine similarity between query and document embeddings\n- **age_days(t)** = days elapsed since document timestamp\n- **h** = half-life in days (default 14 days)\n\nThe exponential decay component ensures older documents gradually become less relevant, with importance halving every `h` days.\n\n## Practical Parameters\n\n| Parameter | Default | Use Case |\n|-----------|---------|----------|\n| α (alpha) | 0.7 | Balanced semantic-temporal weighting |\n| Half-life (h) | 14 days | Enterprise information lifecycle |\n| Query scope | 7 days | Freshness-focused retrieval |\n\nThe authors note α values of 0.4–0.7 maintain perfect accuracy; values ≥0.9 degrade to 66.7% as semantic similarity dominates.\n\n## Limits of Heuristic Approaches\n\nThe paper reveals critical failures in simple heuristic trend detection. Their K-means clustering baseline achieved only 0.08 F1-score for identifying topic dynamics (growth/drift/decay). Key limitations:\n\n- **Fixed K assumption**: Real-world data showed unstable optimal clusters (K=3 to K=9 weekly)\n- **Spherical clusters**: Semantic topics are often non-convex, violating K-means assumptions\n- **High dimensionality**: The 384-dimensional embedding space makes Euclidean distance less meaningful\n\nThe authors conclude that basic freshness is tractable, but nuanced topic evolution remains an open challenge requiring probabilistic methods like Dynamic Topic Models.","durationMs":6946,"url":"https://arxiv.org/html/2509.19376"},"sourceToolAssistantUUID":"ecb3e0f4-548e-43ec-844a-d2a16e6fd7ef","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main"}
