{"parentUuid":"615366ed-cbfc-42f2-9e36-29034f7e9c35","isSidechain":true,"agentId":"a0c75e73218e5c8e8","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-8","id":"msg_018PwnXykt7Ko1yFbWeXVt2k","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01KSTGnsQfvyx1ryHe6fBQoH","name":"WebSearch","input":{"query":"fine-tuning LoRA QLoRA 16GB Apple Silicon Mac MLX feasibility 8B model memory constraints"},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":"tool_use","stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":2,"cache_creation_input_tokens":2604,"cache_read_input_tokens":21535,"output_tokens":236,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":2604},"inference_geo":"not_available","iterations":[{"input_tokens":2,"output_tokens":236,"cache_read_input_tokens":21535,"cache_creation_input_tokens":2604,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":2604,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"type":"message"}],"speed":"standard"},"diagnostics":null},"requestId":"req_011CcFiySGNwGyRRaMqQkTgw","attributionAgent":"general-purpose","type":"assistant","uuid":"41afaa6e-6f7f-40d9-8684-7a85e3c87cbd","timestamp":"2026-06-21T03:50:50.811Z","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main"}
{"parentUuid":"41afaa6e-6f7f-40d9-8684-7a85e3c87cbd","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"ed988829-c186-4cf7-8fda-2a36bf7006f0","agentId":"a0c75e73218e5c8e8","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01KSTGnsQfvyx1ryHe6fBQoH","type":"tool_result","content":"Web search results for query: \"fine-tuning LoRA QLoRA 16GB Apple Silicon Mac MLX feasibility 8B model memory constraints\"\n\nLinks: [{\"title\":\"Fine-Tuning on Mac: LoRA & QLoRA with MLX | InsiderLLM\",\"url\":\"https://insiderllm.com/guides/fine-tuning-mac-lora-mlx/\"},{\"title\":\"Train Your Own LLM on MacBook: A Fine-tuning Guide with MLX | by Dushyant Mahajan | Medium\",\"url\":\"https://medium.com/@dummahajan/train-your-own-llm-on-macbook-a-15-minute-guide-with-mlx-6c6ed9ad036a\"},{\"title\":\"LoRA Fine-Tuning On Your Apple Silicon MacBook | Towards Data Science\",\"url\":\"https://towardsdatascience.com/lora-fine-tuning-on-your-apple-silicon-macbook-432c7dab614a/\"},{\"title\":\"The Hitchhiker’s Guide to Fine Tune LLMs on a Mac | by Rhitam Deb | Medium\",\"url\":\"https://medium.com/@neevdeb26/the-hitchhikers-guide-to-fine-tune-llms-on-a-mac-85174455457a\"},{\"title\":\"MLX Apple Silicon AI Dev Stack: Fine-Tune LLMs on Mac\",\"url\":\"https://www.buildmvpfast.com/blog/mlx-apple-silicon-ai-development-mac-fine-tune-llm-2026\"},{\"title\":\"Run and Fine-Tune LLMs on Mac with MLX-LM 2026 | Markaicode\",\"url\":\"https://markaicode.com/run-fine-tune-llms-mac-mlx-lm/\"},{\"title\":\"Fine-Tuning LLMs Locally Using MLX LM\",\"url\":\"https://dzone.com/articles/fine-tuning-llms-locally-using-mlx-lm-guide\"},{\"title\":\"Fine-Tuning LLMs with LoRA and MLX-LM | by Joana Levtcheva | Medium\",\"url\":\"https://medium.com/@levchevajoana/fine-tuning-llms-with-lora-and-mlx-lm-c0b143642deb\"},{\"title\":\"How to Fine-Tune a Small LLM on a Laptop: Hardware Guide\",\"url\":\"https://www.laptophub.net/how-to-fine-tune-small-llm-on-laptop/\"},{\"title\":\"How to Fine-Tune LLMs Locally: The Complete LoRA Guide\",\"url\":\"https://medium.com/@matteo28/how-to-fine-tune-llms-locally-the-complete-lora-guide-420fe9e1278d\"}]\n\nBased on the search results, here's what I found regarding fine-tuning LoRA/QLoRA on a 16GB Apple Silicon Mac with MLX for 8B models:\n\n## Feasibility: Yes, Highly Feasible\n\nQLoRA on a 16GB MacBook fine-tunes an 8B model in about an hour. This is directly supported by the MLX framework.\n\n## Memory Constraints & Configuration\n\nThe big advantage is unified memory means no VRAM wall. A 32GB M2 Pro can fine-tune models that would crash an RTX 3090 (24GB). For 16GB machines, the approach is slightly more constrained but still viable:\n\n- Start with 8 for quick experiments, increase to 16–32 for production adapters on 16GB+ machines.\n- On a 16GB M2 MacBook Pro, you can run Mistral 7B at ~40 tokens/sec and fine-tune a LoRA adapter on a custom dataset in under 30 minutes.\n\n## Practical Recommendations\n\nFor memory-constrained 16GB setups:\n- If you still face issues, consider reducing batch-size, num-layers, or using a smaller base model. MLX also supports grad-checkpoint to trade some speed for lower memory usage.\n- For quantized models (QLoRA), use MLX-format quantized versions from the mlx-community org on HuggingFace, or quantize yourself. QLoRA produces slightly lower quality than full-precision LoRA because the base weights are approximated at 4-bit. For most practical tasks the difference is small. If you're on the edge of fitting, use QLoRA and don't worry about it.\n\n## Quick Start\n\nInstall mlx-lm, point it at a HuggingFace model, give it a JSONL file with 200-500 examples, and run mlx_lm.lora --train.\n\nThe 16GB unified memory constraint is manageable for 8B models with proper configuration, especially using QLoRA with quantized base models.\n\n\nREMINDER: You MUST include the sources above in your response to the user using markdown hyperlinks."}]},"uuid":"d5d5330b-bc2e-46d1-ba53-19e967acb1f5","timestamp":"2026-06-21T03:51:00.639Z","toolUseResult":{"query":"fine-tuning LoRA QLoRA 16GB Apple Silicon Mac MLX feasibility 8B model memory constraints","results":[{"tool_use_id":"srvtoolu_01NHDxrFe7sNLtyfX7mU9bko","content":[{"title":"Fine-Tuning on Mac: LoRA & QLoRA with MLX | InsiderLLM","url":"https://insiderllm.com/guides/fine-tuning-mac-lora-mlx/"},{"title":"Train Your Own LLM on MacBook: A Fine-tuning Guide with MLX | by Dushyant Mahajan | Medium","url":"https://medium.com/@dummahajan/train-your-own-llm-on-macbook-a-15-minute-guide-with-mlx-6c6ed9ad036a"},{"title":"LoRA Fine-Tuning On Your Apple Silicon MacBook | Towards Data Science","url":"https://towardsdatascience.com/lora-fine-tuning-on-your-apple-silicon-macbook-432c7dab614a/"},{"title":"The Hitchhiker’s Guide to Fine Tune LLMs on a Mac | by Rhitam Deb | Medium","url":"https://medium.com/@neevdeb26/the-hitchhikers-guide-to-fine-tune-llms-on-a-mac-85174455457a"},{"title":"MLX Apple Silicon AI Dev Stack: Fine-Tune LLMs on Mac","url":"https://www.buildmvpfast.com/blog/mlx-apple-silicon-ai-development-mac-fine-tune-llm-2026"},{"title":"Run and Fine-Tune LLMs on Mac with MLX-LM 2026 | Markaicode","url":"https://markaicode.com/run-fine-tune-llms-mac-mlx-lm/"},{"title":"Fine-Tuning LLMs Locally Using MLX LM","url":"https://dzone.com/articles/fine-tuning-llms-locally-using-mlx-lm-guide"},{"title":"Fine-Tuning LLMs with LoRA and MLX-LM | by Joana Levtcheva | Medium","url":"https://medium.com/@levchevajoana/fine-tuning-llms-with-lora-and-mlx-lm-c0b143642deb"},{"title":"How to Fine-Tune a Small LLM on a Laptop: Hardware Guide","url":"https://www.laptophub.net/how-to-fine-tune-small-llm-on-laptop/"},{"title":"How to Fine-Tune LLMs Locally: The Complete LoRA Guide","url":"https://medium.com/@matteo28/how-to-fine-tune-llms-locally-the-complete-lora-guide-420fe9e1278d"}]},"Based on the search results, here's what I found regarding fine-tuning LoRA/QLoRA on a 16GB Apple Silicon Mac with MLX for 8B models:\n\n## Feasibility: Yes, Highly Feasible\n\nQLoRA on a 16GB MacBook fine-tunes an 8B model in about an hour. This is directly supported by the MLX framework.\n\n## Memory Constraints & Configuration\n\nThe big advantage is unified memory means no VRAM wall. A 32GB M2 Pro can fine-tune models that would crash an RTX 3090 (24GB). For 16GB machines, the approach is slightly more constrained but still viable:\n\n- Start with 8 for quick experiments, increase to 16–32 for production adapters on 16GB+ machines.\n- On a 16GB M2 MacBook Pro, you can run Mistral 7B at ~40 tokens/sec and fine-tune a LoRA adapter on a custom dataset in under 30 minutes.\n\n## Practical Recommendations\n\nFor memory-constrained 16GB setups:\n- If you still face issues, consider reducing batch-size, num-layers, or using a smaller base model. MLX also supports grad-checkpoint to trade some speed for lower memory usage.\n- For quantized models (QLoRA), use MLX-format quantized versions from the mlx-community org on HuggingFace, or quantize yourself. QLoRA produces slightly lower quality than full-precision LoRA because the base weights are approximated at 4-bit. For most practical tasks the difference is small. If you're on the edge of fitting, use QLoRA and don't worry about it.\n\n## Quick Start\n\nInstall mlx-lm, point it at a HuggingFace model, give it a JSONL file with 200-500 examples, and run mlx_lm.lora --train.\n\nThe 16GB unified memory constraint is manageable for 8B models with proper configuration, especially using QLoRA with quantized base models."],"durationSeconds":9.62426329199999,"searchCount":1},"sourceToolAssistantUUID":"41afaa6e-6f7f-40d9-8684-7a85e3c87cbd","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main"}
{"parentUuid":"615366ed-cbfc-42f2-9e36-29034f7e9c35","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"ed988829-c186-4cf7-8fda-2a36bf7006f0","agentId":"a0c75e73218e5c8e8","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01TXY2P4yHHxvW8juDiaEiGf","type":"tool_result","content":"Web search results for query: \"LongMemEval results retrieval improves long-context LLM accuracy fixed model memory design\"\n\nLinks: [{\"title\":\"LongMemEval: Benchmark for LLM Memory\",\"url\":\"https://www.emergentmind.com/topics/longmemeval-dataset\"},{\"title\":\"LongMemEval: LLM Long-Term Memory Benchmark\",\"url\":\"https://www.emergentmind.com/topics/longmemeval\"},{\"title\":\"LongMemEval: Benchmarking Chat Assist- ants on Long-Term Interactive Memory\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/html/2410.10813v1\"},{\"title\":\"[2410.10813] LongMemEval: Benchmarking Chat Assistants on Long-Term Interactive Memory\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/abs/2410.10813\"},{\"title\":\"longmemeval: benchmarking chat assist\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2410.10813\"},{\"title\":\"HyMem: Hybrid Memory Architecture with Dynamic Retrieval Scheduling\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2602.13933\"},{\"title\":\"LongMemEval\",\"url\":\"https://xiaowu0162.github.io/long-mem-eval/\"},{\"title\":\"MemMachine: A Ground-Truth-Preserving Memory System for Personalized AI Agents\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2604.04853\"},{\"title\":\"Benchmarking Memoria on LongMemEval: Strong Memory Retrieval, Clear Reader Separation | by MatrixOrigin | Medium\",\"url\":\"https://medium.com/@matrixorigin-database/benchmarking-memoria-on-longmemeval-strong-memory-retrieval-clear-reader-separation-ee6c89c75d76\"}]\n\nBased on the search results, here's what I found about LongMemEval and how retrieval improvements affect long-context LLM accuracy:\n\n## LongMemEval Overview\n\nLongMemEval is a comprehensive benchmark designed to evaluate five core long-term memory abilities of chat assistants: information extraction, multi-session reasoning, temporal reasoning, knowledge updates, and abstention.\n\n## Performance Challenges with Fixed Model Memory\n\nLong-context LLMs showed a 30% to 60% performance decline when tasked with reading the entire LongMemEvalS history, compared to oracle retrieval settings where they answer with only the evidence sessions as context. This demonstrates that how data is recalled matters more than how it is stored, provided the storage preserves ground truth.\n\n## Retrieval-Based Improvements\n\nMemory design optimizations include session decomposition for value granularity, fact-augmented key expansion for indexing, and time-aware query expansion for refining the search scope. More specifically:\n\n- Fine-grained session decomposition slices sessions into rounds to improve token efficiency and retrieval targeting, particularly enhancing performance on complex, multi-session reasoning tasks.\n- Applying Chain-of-Note and structured JSON prompt format improves the reading accuracy by as much as 10 absolute points across three LLMs.\n\nRetrieval-stage optimizations contribute substantially more to final accuracy than ingestion-stage changes, with retrieval-side improvements cumulatively contributing far more than ingestion-side changes.\n\n\nREMINDER: You MUST include the sources above in your response to the user using markdown hyperlinks."}]},"uuid":"e92ebbfb-bfa8-4822-9ecc-08ad88989b18","timestamp":"2026-06-21T03:51:01.073Z","toolUseResult":{"query":"LongMemEval results retrieval improves long-context LLM accuracy fixed model memory design","results":[{"tool_use_id":"srvtoolu_01Sv8jXr2UFRuW3975e36ueC","content":[{"title":"LongMemEval: Benchmark for LLM Memory","url":"https://www.emergentmind.com/topics/longmemeval-dataset"},{"title":"LongMemEval: LLM Long-Term Memory Benchmark","url":"https://www.emergentmind.com/topics/longmemeval"},{"title":"LongMemEval: Benchmarking Chat Assist- ants on Long-Term Interactive Memory","url":"https://arxiv.org/html/2410.10813v1"},{"title":"[2410.10813] LongMemEval: Benchmarking Chat Assistants on Long-Term Interactive Memory","url":"https://arxiv.org/abs/2410.10813"},{"title":"longmemeval: benchmarking chat assist","url":"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2410.10813"},{"title":"HyMem: Hybrid Memory Architecture with Dynamic Retrieval Scheduling","url":"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2602.13933"},{"title":"LongMemEval","url":"https://xiaowu0162.github.io/long-mem-eval/"},{"title":"MemMachine: A Ground-Truth-Preserving Memory System for Personalized AI Agents","url":"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2604.04853"},{"title":"Benchmarking Memoria on LongMemEval: Strong Memory Retrieval, Clear Reader Separation | by MatrixOrigin | Medium","url":"https://medium.com/@matrixorigin-database/benchmarking-memoria-on-longmemeval-strong-memory-retrieval-clear-reader-separation-ee6c89c75d76"}]},"Based on the search results, here's what I found about LongMemEval and how retrieval improvements affect long-context LLM accuracy:\n\n## LongMemEval Overview\n\nLongMemEval is a comprehensive benchmark designed to evaluate five core long-term memory abilities of chat assistants: information extraction, multi-session reasoning, temporal reasoning, knowledge updates, and abstention.\n\n## Performance Challenges with Fixed Model Memory\n\nLong-context LLMs showed a 30% to 60% performance decline when tasked with reading the entire LongMemEvalS history, compared to oracle retrieval settings where they answer with only the evidence sessions as context. This demonstrates that how data is recalled matters more than how it is stored, provided the storage preserves ground truth.\n\n## Retrieval-Based Improvements\n\nMemory design optimizations include session decomposition for value granularity, fact-augmented key expansion for indexing, and time-aware query expansion for refining the search scope. More specifically:\n\n- Fine-grained session decomposition slices sessions into rounds to improve token efficiency and retrieval targeting, particularly enhancing performance on complex, multi-session reasoning tasks.\n- Applying Chain-of-Note and structured JSON prompt format improves the reading accuracy by as much as 10 absolute points across three LLMs.\n\nRetrieval-stage optimizations contribute substantially more to final accuracy than ingestion-stage changes, with retrieval-side improvements cumulatively contributing far more than ingestion-side changes."],"durationSeconds":10.294213999999979,"searchCount":1},"sourceToolAssistantUUID":"615366ed-cbfc-42f2-9e36-29034f7e9c35","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main"}
{"parentUuid":"e92ebbfb-bfa8-4822-9ecc-08ad88989b18","isSidechain":true,"agentId":"a0c75e73218e5c8e8","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-8","id":"msg_01RZsAJtW1HZb6tS3bQUZSuB","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"I now have comprehensive material across all four research areas. Let me synthesize the findings.\n\n---\n\n# Research findings: Token-space compounding for Yogi M3\n\n## 1. Evidence that memory consolidation + retrieval yield measurable, growing performance (model fixed)\n\nThe evidence is real and quantified, but with an important nuance: **the strongest gains come from retrieval/recall, not from storage/consolidation alone.**\n\n- **LongMemEval** is the cleanest \"model-held-constant\" evidence. The same long-context LLM shows a **30–60% accuracy drop** when forced to read the entire interaction history versus an oracle-retrieval setting where it sees only the evidence sessions. Their conclusion: *\"how data is recalled matters more than how it is stored, provided the storage preserves ground truth,\"* and *\"retrieval-stage optimizations contribute substantially more to final accuracy than ingestion-stage changes.\"* Structured reading (Chain-of-Note + JSON) adds up to **+10 absolute points** across three LLMs — all with frozen weights. (https://arxiv.org/abs/2410.10813, https://arxiv.org/html/2410.10813v1)\n\n- **Mem0** reports 92.5% on LoCoMo / 94.4% on LongMemEval at <7K tokens/query vs 25K+ for full-context, with the biggest lifts on temporal queries (+29.6) and multi-hop (+23.1) on LoCoMo. Caveat: their public page does **not** give a clean no-memory baseline delta — gains are stated as absolute scores and token savings, not rigorously isolated \"memory vs none.\" (https://mem0.ai/research, https://mem0.ai/blog/ai-memory-benchmarks-in-2026)\n\n- **A-MEM** (agentic Zettelkasten-style memory with LLM-generated links/consolidation) reports SOTA over baselines across six foundation models, with a near six-fold improvement on multi-hop — again, model fixed, gains from memory structure. (https://arxiv.org/abs/2502.12110, https://arxiv.org/html/2502.12110v1)\n\n- **BEAM (2026)** shows structured memory beats the strongest long-context baseline by **3.5–12.7%**, widening at larger scales — i.e. long context alone does not substitute for memory. (https://mem0.ai/blog/ai-memory-benchmarks-in-2026)\n\n**Bottom line:** measurable, fixed-model improvement from token-space memory is well-supported, but the load-bearing component is *retrieval quality*, not the act of consolidation. Consolidation matters mainly insofar as it makes retrieval cleaner.\n\n## 2. Memory/retrieval vs weight distillation — how much compounding is realistic?\n\n- **Letta's \"Continual Learning in Token Space\"** is the strongest articulation of the thesis: learning lives in context (prompts, tool defs, memories), not weights. Advantages: human-readable/inspectable, portable across models/generations, trivially reversible (delete tokens), versionable like text. But note — this specific post is **a research agenda, largely conceptual, with no empirical compounding numbers.** (https://www.letta.com/blog/continual-learning)\n\n- **Letta's \"Skill Learning\"** is where the empirical backing lives, and it's the most relevant result for Yogi. Agents reflect on task trajectories and write structured skill files (markdown), retrieved on demand. On **Terminal Bench 2.0** with the model held constant: **+21.1% relative (9% absolute)** from trajectory-derived skills, rising to **+36.8% relative (15.7% absolute)** when skills incorporate verifier/error feedback — plus 15.7% cost reduction and 10.4% fewer tool calls. This is direct evidence that token-space skill accumulation compounds task performance. (https://www.letta.com/blog/skill-learning)\n\n- Letta argues fine-tuning is poorly suited to *continual online* learning: LoRA-style methods are offline-eval-shaped, require curated data + human oversight per update, and face catastrophic forgetting and recency-weighting problems. Their framing: persistent memory can reach *\"performance comparable to fine-tuned models while remaining flexible and debuggable.\"* (https://www.letta.com/blog/continual-learning, https://www.letta.com/blog/skill-learning)\n\n**Realistic split:** token-space (memory + retrieval + skill/prompt updates with verifier feedback) is a credible *primary* compounding mechanism — double-digit absolute task gains are demonstrated, model fixed. The decisive ingredient is a **verifier/error-feedback signal** feeding skill refinement (Letta's 9%→15.7% jump). Weight distillation is best framed as a *latency/cost compression* step (Letta lists distillation as the eventual \"tokens → weights\" optimization), not the source of new capability.\n\n## 3. Practical local RAG with `nomic-embed-text`\n\n- **Dimension / similarity:** 768-dim; trained with **cosine/dot-product** (normalize, then dot = cosine). v2-moe supports Matryoshka truncation (e.g. 256) if you want cheaper vectors. (https://huggingface.co/nomic-ai/nomic-embed-text-v2-moe, https://arxiv.org/html/2402.01613v2)\n- **Hybrid (dense + BM25):** combine cosine top-k with a BM25/sparse index via **reciprocal rank fusion**; reported **+15–30% recall** over either alone, and specifically important for code/identifiers (exact-match) and technical jargon. Strongly recommended given Yogi's domain. (search synthesis; ai-marketinglabs hybrid writeup)\n- **Recency/freshness weighting** — concrete, cheap formula from the freshness paper:\n  `score = α·cos(q,d) + (1−α)·0.5^(age_days/h)` with **α≈0.7, half-life h≈14 days**. They found **α in 0.4–0.7 holds accuracy; α≥0.9 degrades to ~67%** (pure semantic surfaces stale facts). (https://arxiv.org/html/2509.19376)\n- **Failure modes to design against:**\n  - *Stale-but-similar:* outdated docs keep scoring high on cosine — \"cosine measures coherence, not correctness.\" Needs the explicit temporal prior above.\n  - *Retrieval drift at scale:* production recall observed degrading **0.92 → 0.74**, relevant docs sliding from rank 2 → rank 8 as memory grows; FIFO eviction discards still-relevant old entries while stale entries accumulate weight. (https://towardsdatascience.com/your-rag-gets-confidently-wrong-as-memory-grows..., dev.to ten-failure-modes)\n  - *Heuristic topic-drift detection is hard:* K-means trend detection scored 0.08 F1 — don't try to auto-detect \"story reframing\" cheaply; stick to recency prior + explicit knowledge-update/supersession links. (https://arxiv.org/html/2509.19376)\n  - Knowledge updates (fact supersession) are a named, separately-scored ability in LongMemEval — handle \"new info overrides old\" explicitly rather than hoping retrieval sorts it out.\n\n## 4. Sequencing for a 16 GB on-device build\n\n- On-device fine-tuning is **viable but marginal** at 16 GB: QLoRA on an 8B in ~30–60 min is reported, but only with reduced batch size, fewer layers, grad-checkpointing, 4-bit base — i.e. it competes directly with your \"one large model at a time\" budget and your hard rule against inference in the automated loop. It's a *foreground, manual, occasional* operation at best. (https://insiderllm.com/guides/fine-tuning-mac-lora-mlx/, https://towardsdatascience.com/lora-fine-tuning-on-your-apple-silicon-macbook-432c7dab614a/)\n- Token-space compounding is **cheap, training-free, inspectable, and reversible** — and (critically for a bench) it produces measurable deltas without ever loading a training run, fitting the \"no model inference in the automated loop\" constraint. Consolidation can run as a foreground \"sleep-time\" pass; retrieval is just embedding + index lookup.\n\nThis strongly favors **M3 leading with token-space**, with distillation as a gated secondary arm.\n\n---\n\n## RECOMMENDATION for Yogi M3\n\n**Make token-space the primary compounding mechanism the bench measures first. Treat per-domain weight distillation as a secondary, optional, foreground-only arm gated behind a proven token-space win.** This matches the evidence (Letta skill learning's 9–15.7% absolute gains, LongMemEval's retrieval dominance) and the 16 GB / no-loop-inference constraints.\n\nStructure it as three layers, in this order:\n\n1. **Retrieval first (highest ROI, lowest cost).** This is where the measured gains concentrate. Build a hybrid retriever over `nomic-embed-text` (768-dim, cosine on normalized vectors) + BM25 with reciprocal rank fusion, plus the recency prior `α·cos + (1−α)·0.5^(age/h)` (α≈0.7, h≈14d, tunable). Make retrieval the first thing the bench varies — LongMemEval shows retrieval changes dominate ingestion changes.\n\n2. **Consolidation second (episodic → semantic).** A foreground \"sleep-time\" pass that distils raw episodes into atomic, linked semantic notes (A-MEM/Zettelkasten style) with explicit supersession edges for knowledge updates. Its job is to *improve retrieval cleanliness*, not to be the win by itself.\n\n3. **Skill/prompt learning as the compounding loop with a verifier.** The decisive lever: reflect on bench trajectories, write structured skill notes, and — crucially — fold in **error/verifier feedback** (Letta's 9%→15.7% jump came from exactly this). Yogi already has a falsification harness (M2 being-bench); wire its pass/fail signal into skill refinement. Skills stored as versioned text fit the \"inspectable, reversible, portable\" properties and your closed-mutation-surface invariants.\n\n**Bench design:** the M2 bench must isolate the compounding delta against a **no-memory / no-skill baseline** on a fixed `qwen3:8b` — run the same task suite (a) cold, (b) with retrieval only, (c) +consolidation, (d) +skill-with-verifier-feedback, tracking accuracy *and* tokens/tool-calls (the Mem0/Letta efficiency dimension). This also directly feeds your M6 anti-theater gate: \"compounding\" must mean a measured upward curve on held-out tasks attributable to memory, not just accumulated context.\n\n**Gate distillation behind this:** only attempt QLoRA per-domain distillation as a *foreground, user-initiated* step once token-space shows a real, sustained bench curve — and frame distillation as latency/cost compression of already-proven token-space skills (Letta's \"tokens → weights\" optimization), never as the primary source of new capability. This keeps the automated loop inference-free and respects the 16 GB one-model-at-a-time budget.\n\n**Top failure modes to encode as tests/guards:** stale-but-similar retrieval (require the temporal prior; don't ship pure cosine), retrieval drift as memory grows (don't use naive FIFO eviction; test recall on a growing corpus), and fact supersession (test knowledge-update queries explicitly).\n\n### Sources\n- https://arxiv.org/abs/2410.10813 · https://arxiv.org/html/2410.10813v1 — LongMemEval\n- https://mem0.ai/research · https://mem0.ai/blog/ai-memory-benchmarks-in-2026 — Mem0 / LoCoMo / BEAM\n- https://arxiv.org/abs/2502.12110 · https://arxiv.org/html/2502.12110v1 — A-MEM\n- https://www.letta.com/blog/continual-learning — Letta continual learning in token space (agenda)\n- https://www.letta.com/blog/skill-learning — Letta Skill Learning (Terminal Bench 2.0 empirical gains)\n- https://huggingface.co/nomic-ai/nomic-embed-text-v2-moe · https://arxiv.org/html/2402.01613v2 — nomic-embed-text dims/similarity\n- https://arxiv.org/html/2509.19376 — recency prior formula + limits of heuristic drift detection\n- https://towardsdatascience.com/your-rag-gets-confidently-wrong-as-memory-grows-i-built-the-memory-layer-that-stops-it/ · https://dev.to/kuldeep_paul/ten-failure-modes-of-rag-nobody-talks-about-and-how-to-detect-them-systematically-7i4 — RAG failure modes / drift\n- https://insiderllm.com/guides/fine-tuning-mac-lora-mlx/ · https://towardsdatascience.com/lora-fine-tuning-on-your-apple-silicon-macbook-432c7dab614a/ — 16 GB MLX QLoRA feasibility"}],"stop_reason":"end_turn","stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1639,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1428,"cache_read_input_tokens":24139,"output_tokens":4497,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":1428},"inference_geo":"not_available","iterations":[{"input_tokens":1639,"output_tokens":4497,"cache_read_input_tokens":24139,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1428,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":1428,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"type":"message"}],"speed":"standard"},"diagnostics":null},"requestId":"req_011CcFizVvvcTeP1Z6hL3fKH","attributionAgent":"general-purpose","type":"assistant","uuid":"944f717d-adcc-47e7-871f-332bef04a33b","timestamp":"2026-06-21T03:52:01.863Z","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main"}
